## A Project of Unprecedented Ambition

The **Sun Birds** of the Reman Empire represent one of the most extraordinary and least-known achievements of Tamrielic civilization. These magical vessels, designed to travel through the sun into **Aetherius** — the plane of pure magic — stand as testament to an era when imperial ambition knew literally no limits, not even the boundaries of reality itself.

Under the **Reman** dynasty, the Second Cyrodilic Empire reached a level of power and magical sophistication rarely equaled in the history of **Tamriel**. The combined resources of an entire empire were mobilized for projects that today seem to border on madness or myth. The Sun Birds were the most ambitious of these projects: nothing less than an attempt to conquer the sky itself.

The concept rested on a precise cosmological understanding: the sun is not a star of fire but a hole in the fabric of **Mundus**, a breach left by **Magnus**, the divine Architect, when he fled from creation. Through this passage, the light of Aetherius floods the mortal world. If a vessel could traverse this opening, it would reach the plane of pure magic — the ultimate source of all supernatural power.

## The Design and Construction

The construction of the Sun Birds mobilized the greatest magical minds of the Empire. Enchanters, alchemists, conjurers, and mystics from all provinces contributed to the project. The materials used were among the most rare and precious in Tamriel: Ayleid Varla crystals, enchanted ebony, lunar metals, and alchemical substances whose formulas are now lost.

Each vessel was a masterpiece of applied magic, as much a work of art as an exploration vehicle. The enchantments protecting it had to withstand traversal through the atmosphere and the void between Mundus and Aetherius — an environment where conventional physical laws cease to apply. The protective shells were woven from preservation spells so complex that a single vessel required years of work.

Propulsion rested on magical principles we no longer understand today. Some texts speak of engines powered by souls, others describe sails catching the magical winds of Aetherius. The surviving descriptions are fragmentary and often contradictory, making an accurate reconstruction of the technology employed impossible.

## The Voyages to Aetherius

The imperial chronicles of this period mention several successful expeditions to Aetherius. The Sun Birds traversed the passage of Magnus and entered the plane of pure magic — a feat most civilizations would consider impossible. Crews returned with descriptions of a realm of infinite light, where magic was not a force to be manipulated but the very environment itself.

Travelers described Aetherius as an ocean of pure creativity, a space where thought and reality were one. The laws governing Mundus — gravity, time, causality — did not exist there in their familiar form. Explorers had to maintain absolute mental discipline to avoid dissolving into the ambient flow of magic.

Some expeditions brought back materials of incalculable value: samples of pure aetherial substance, crystals that radiated permanent magic, and fragments of knowledge encoded in light itself. These treasures fueled the Empire's magical research for decades and helped maintain the technological supremacy of the Reman dynasty.

## The Dangers and the Losses

Voyages to Aetherius were not without risk. Several Sun Birds never returned, lost in the unpredictable currents of the magical plane or destroyed during the crossing. Crews that survived often returned changed: some had aged by decades in a matter of days, others had become partially translucent, and a few had lost the ability to perceive the physical world normally.

Prolonged exposure to the pure magic of Aetherius had unpredictable effects on mortals. Some travelers developed extraordinary but uncontrollable magical abilities. Others gradually lost their corporeality, becoming increasingly ethereal until they vanished completely. The crew attrition rate was such that recruitment became progressively more difficult.

Accounts from survivors also mention hostile entities encountered within Aetherius. Contrary to the popular vision of Aetherius as a paradise of light, the plane appears to harbor powerful and territorial creatures who did not look favorably upon mortal intrusions. Some losses were attributed to attacks by these aetherial guardians.

## The Decline of the Program

The Sun Bird program declined alongside the Reman dynasty itself. The astronomical costs of the project, combined with human and material losses, made its continuation politically difficult. The wars against **Akavir** and the Empire's internal troubles diverted resources toward more immediate priorities. Gradually, launches became infrequent and then ceased entirely.

The knowledge required to build and pilot the Sun Birds was lost along with the craftsmen and mages who possessed it. Technical manuscripts were dispersed, destroyed, or forgotten in imperial libraries. By the end of the First Era, the program was nothing more than a memory — a legend told in magical academies as an example of the Empire's former greatness.

The assassination of the last **Akaviri Potentate** and the turmoil that followed erased the final traces of the program. Launch facilities were abandoned or repurposed. The few surviving Sun Birds were dismantled to recover their precious magical components. An era of bold exploration ended in oblivion and neglect.

## A Legacy of Possibilities

The very existence of the Sun Birds raises a troubling question: what have we lost? If the Reman Empire could reach Aetherius, what other feats were within reach of a civilization unafraid to challenge the limits of reality? The technological and magical regression that followed the fall of the Reman dynasty suggests that progress is not linear, and that knowledge once gained can be lost forever.

The rare scholars who still study the subject hope that one day, the plans for the Sun Birds will be rediscovered and that voyages to Aetherius will resume. But most regard the program as a historical curiosity — the grandiose folly of a vanished empire. In a world that has forgotten how to reach the stars, the Sun Birds remain a reminder that human ambition has, in principle, no limits — even if reality often brings it back to earth.
